items.title: Olearia rugosa subsp. allenderae
items.content_text: subsp. allenderae (newly named) only occurs at Wilsons Prom. See cordate leaf base at the bottom of pic2 which is a key feature.

items.title: Caladenia parva
items.content_text: Despite the clubbed petals this is most likely phaeoclavia.

items.title: Patersonia glabrata
items.content_text: 1st pic shows broad hyaline bract margin. 2nd pic shows fan-shaped leaf base in multiple tufts.

items.title: Sphaerolobium minus
items.content_text: Could be a new species record for the Prom - more checking to do.

items.title: Vellereophyton dealbatum
items.content_text: Large stands of this weed are colonising the areas where the landslips occurred a few years ago.

items.title: Silene gallica var. quinquevulnera
items.content_text: Appears to be a new species record for Wilsons Prom.

items.title: Geranium potentilloides var. potentilloides
items.content_text: Short, soft hairs, orange anthers, good sized mucro on sepals, single flower.

items.title: Geranium homeanum
items.content_text: Very long sepal mucro, elliptic sepals, whitish anthers and long curved hairs pointing back down stem.

items.title: Phyllanthus gunnii
items.content_text: 2m shrub with distinctive foliage and flowers with 6 petals (and 6 sepals). The latter is rare among dicots.

items.title: Caladenia dilatata s.l.
items.content_text: Probably C. phaeoclavia.

items.title: Thelymitra malvina
items.content_text: Along with previous observation (10253), this shows the limits of the positions where this new species record for Wilsons Prom was seen - about 6-10 plants seen on the side of the track. Plants were open in pouring rain (no sun).

items.title: Thelymitra malvina
items.content_text: New species record for Wilsons Prom. Nearest records are west of Korumburra and Providence Ponds Reserve (east of Sale). Distinctive mauve tufts on column arms. Apparently opens only in mornings. These were open in pouring rain (no sun).

items.title: Caladenia aurantiaca
items.content_text: Small flower on tallish stem. Out in the pouring rain.
